entry.title: Allow peeking at the gpu::Mailbox used by a GPUTexture.
entry.content:
`endWebGPUAccess` will need to retrieve the gpu::Mailbox from an

existing GPUTexture. This should always be possible because we

control `beginWebGPUAccess`, and its textures are created in a

predictable way (via a shared image). The prerequisite accessors

are added in this CL. Also, GPUTextures now hold on to the

gpu::Mailbox name post-construction, so it can be retrieved later.

These are small (16 bytes?) so should be a negligible cost.



`endWebGPUAccess` now invokes the accessors and checks that they

returned reasonable values. In a followup, the mailbox will be used

to replace the canvas' image.

entry.title: reclient: Set -lifetime 5m for luci-auth
entry.content:
reproxy wants to refresh a token once its lifetime is less than 5

minutes. However, luci-auth by default does not refresh a token until

its lifetime is less than 1 minute.



This leads to reproxy asking luci-auth for a new token too early, which

causes luci-auth to just return the same token as before, which causes

reproxy to become very confused why luci-auth doesn't understand the

urgency of the situation. Flabbergasted about luci-auth's unwillingness

to cooperate, reproxy has some sort of a black-out and forgets

everything it was ever taught about how to handle tokens correctly. All

requests start to fail with an "Unauthenticated" error and the build

fails.



Luckily luci-auth has a flag to set the minimum lifetime for token

reason UseWritePixelsYUV was disabled for unsupported color spaces in

M124 as well. This can potentially happen on any platform.

entry.title: Sync: Remove barrier from GetEntityCountsForDebugging
entry.content:
SyncServiceImpl::GetEntityCountsForDebugging() is used by sync-internals

to display the number of entities for each data type.



Before this CL: The implementation waited for the counts from all data

types to arrive before returning the combined result via a OnceCallback.



This breaks if any single data type is in a bad state and doesn't

return its count.



After this CL: The implementation returns the result for each data type

separately (to a RepeatingCallback). This is more robust when

individual data types misbehave.

entry.title: [PartitionAlloc] Remove __assume_aligned__() from PartitionAlloc
entry.content:
While PartitionAlloc always aligns its allocations on kAlignment, this

is not the case when an allocation is routed to GWP-ASAN, which will put

it (on purpose) as close as possible to the end of a page.



Since we don't know at compile-time when GWP-ASAN is enabled, remove the

annotation. Note that the malloc()-like functions are still marked with

a malloc attribute, so we don't lose everything (depending on the compiler).

entry.title: [//media] Remove usage of GetPlatformSpecificTextureTarget()
entry.content:
MailboxVideoFrameConverter invokes GetPlatformSpecificTextureTarget().

This class is created only on ChromeOS and Linux [1]. For ChromeOS and

Linux the platform-specific texture target is

GL_TEXTURE_EXTERNAL_OES [2]. This CL hardcodes that target as part of

removing all usage of GetPlatformSpecificTextureTarget() outside of

ClientSharedImage.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:media/gpu/chromeos/mailbox_video_frame_converter.h;l=90;bpv=1;bpt=1?q=MailboxVideoFrameConverter&ss=chromium

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:gpu/command_buffer/common/gpu_memory_buffer_support.cc;l=184-186?q=GetPlatformSpecificTextur&ss=chromium

> camera: Move taking state back after preparation

entry.title: Change printing::LooksLikePdf() to take a span of uint8_t
entry.content:
It is common for functions to take either a span or a

string_view to represent a view into some contiguous data.

LooksLikePdf() takes a span, which is an odd choice. Change

LooksLikePdf() to use the more common span type and

adjust callers to match. Most callers are simpler as a result, except in

PdfBlobDataFlattener, where the data is coming from a callback that

returns a string.



Note that PDFs can contain binary data, including NULs, so it does not

make sense to treat PDF data as a string.

entry.title: Revert "Mark WeakLinkNode sequence checking expensive"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 6f447d5040c0c6e619e51ccc53fe0d084c98e896.



Reason for revert: Crashes on ChromeOS as soon as I touch the

device's touchpad



2024-03-26T00:58:16.588106Z FATAL chrome[5433:5496]: [sequence_checker.cc(21)] Check failed: checker.CalledOnValidSequence(&bound_at).

#0 0x56f06aa34da2 base::debug::CollectStackTrace()

#1 0x56f06aa19ba2 base::debug::StackTrace::StackTrace()

#2 0x56f06a934073 logging::LogMessage::Flush()

#3 0x56f063de6fcd logging::LogMessage::~LogMessage()

#4 0x56f06a92053c logging::(anonymous namespace)::DCheckLogMessage::~DCheckLogMessage()

#5 0x56f06a9205ae logging::(anonymous namespace)::DCheckLogMessage::~DCheckLogMessage()

#6 0x56f063dc2ba6 logging::CheckError::~CheckError()

#7 0x56f063de9d22 base::ScopedValidateSequenceChecker::ScopedValidateSequenceChecker()

#8 0x56f063de4706 base::ObserverList<>::begin()

#9 0x56f06bfa75eb ui::CursorController::SetCursorLocation()

#10 0x56f0646d9be5 ui::DrmCursor::SetCursorLocationLocked()

#11 0x56f0646da6bf ui::DrmCursor::MoveCursor()

#12 0x56f06bfd76e6 ui::GestureInterpreterLibevdevCros::OnGestureMove()





Original change's description:

> Mark WeakLinkNode sequence checking expensive

>

> This makes for-each-node sequence checking expensive (which seems

> redundant). As a compromise we do non-"expensive" sequence checking in

> ObserverList::begin(), which should provide the same level of protection

> unless iterators are passed between sequences, which would be one heck

> of a thing to try to do.

>

> This accounts for about 60% of sequence checking in a profile I did way

> back. I have not profiled to see how much sequence checking remains with

> the sequence checking moved to begin() nor do I know the average

> ObserverList size. Let's try it out.

>

> In the same profile (though I don't remember what I profiled) sequence

> checking accounted for 1.2% of cycles. Hopefully this explains some of

> the performance gap between a DCHECK and regular Canary build.

>
